SIMPLE: expiration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expiration
<hw>Ex`pi*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>expiratio</ets>,<ets>exspiratio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>expiration</ets>. See <er>Expire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of expiring</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd><fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The
act or process of breathing out, or forcing air from the lungs through
the nose or mouth; <as>as, respiration consists of inspiration and
<ex>expiration</ex></as>; -- opposed to <ant>inspiration</ant>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Emission of volatile matter; exhalation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The true cause of cold is an <qex>expiration</qex> from the globe
of the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The last emission of breath; death.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The groan of <xex>expiration</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Rambler.</au></rj></p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>A coming to a close; cessation; extinction;
termination; end.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before the <qex>expiration</qex> of thy time.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is expired; matter breathed forth; that
which is produced by breathing out, as a sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The aspirate ⟦ldquo⟧he,⟦rdquo⟧ which is . . . a gentle
<qex>expiration</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. Sharp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>expiration-dated</ent>⟦br⟧
